{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.4.0"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceId":12539165,"sourceType":"datasetVersion","datasetId":7916142},{"sourceId":12539166,"sourceType":"datasetVersion","datasetId":7916143}],"dockerImageVersionId":30749,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/taidinh5/qvi-data-analytics-task-one?scriptVersionId=255517930\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"\n\n<h1 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight:bold;\"\"> <center> Quantium Virtual Internship: Task One </center> </h1>\n<p><center font-family:cursive;\">Author: Tai Dinh</center></p>\n\n***\n\n","metadata":{"_uuid":"051d70d956493feee0c6d64651c6a088724dca2a","_execution_state":"idle"},"attachments":{"98431c4c-861a-4001-b9c3-ceed6a96ad75.png":{"image/png":""},"5c9a2c5a-648e-438e-b28a-15aba98ddba0.png":{"image/png":""},"2b3b4a75-bb85-4b50-96b2-b0a773c73630.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"height:5px; background-color:#0096FF;\"></div>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h2 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight: bold;\"\"> 1. Background Information  </h2>\n\n<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>🖼️ Business Objective:</b><br>\n  As part of Quantium’s Retail Analytics Team, send a report to Julia, based on our analytics from the previous tasks. We want to provide her with insights and recommendations that she can use when developing the strategic plan for the next half year.\n</div>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>📌 Project Tasks:</b><br>\n  •&nbsp; Clean transaction data - fix missing values, outliers, and category errors.<br>\n  •&nbsp; Clean customer data - handle nulls, merge for analysis.<br>\n  •&nbsp; Analyze metrics - total sales, key drivers, top locations, trends.<br>\n  •&nbsp; Draw visualizations - create graphs, charts, note any other insights.<br>\n  •&nbsp; Segment customers - identify key groups, packet size preferences, and target segments.<br>\n  •&nbsp; Save all outputs - cleaned data, CSVs, and visualizations for the final report.\n</div>\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"height:5px; background-color:#0096FF;\"></div>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h2 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight: bold;\"\"> 2. Import Necessary Libraries & Datasets  </h2>\n\n<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>🚧 Data Preparation:</b><br>\n  In this stage, I will prepare the data for analysis by installing and loading any necessary dependencies. After earning the Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate, I developed a strong foundation in R programming, which I will be using to complete task one.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Step 1: Install package(s) \ninstall.packages(c(\"tidyverse\", \"ggmosaic\"))\n\n# Step 2: Load libraries\nlibrary(tidyverse)\nlibrary(ggplot2) #for data visualization\nlibrary(ggmosaic) #for visualizing categorical data\nlibrary(dplyr) #for data manipulation\nlibrary(tidyr) #for tidying messy data\nlibrary(purrr) #for working with functions and lists\nlibrary(tibble) #for a modern version of data frames\nlibrary(stringr) #for wokring with strings\nlibrary(forcats) #for handling factors\nlibrary(readr) #for reading data into R\n\n# (OPTIONAL) Step 3: Set file path (if running R on local RStudio on Windows machine)\n# [ABSOLUTE PATH] filePath <- \"C:/Users/YourName/Downloads/my_dataset.csv\"\n# [RELATIVE PATH] filePath <- \"subfolder/my_dataset.csv\"\n# setwd(\"C:/Users/YourName/Downloads/my_dataset.csv\")\n\n# Step 4: Load data\ntransactionData <- read_csv(\"/kaggle/input/transactiondata/QVI_transaction_data.csv\")\ncustomerData <- read_csv(\"/kaggle/input/customerdata/QVI_purchase_behaviour.csv\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"height:5px; background-color:#0096FF;\"></div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h2 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight: bold;\"\"> 3. Exploratory Data Analysis  </h2>\n\n<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>🛠️ Data Processing:</b><br>\n  In this stage, I will be performing an EDA to better understand the data through visualizations, assessing data quality, detecting anomalies, identifying patterns and calculating descriptive statistics.\n</div>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#FFCCCB; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #EE4B2B; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🦝 Data Raccoon 🦝</b><br>\n  *digging* into transactionData to uncover dirty data and patterns...\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine \"transactionData\" dataset (internal structure)\nstr(transactionData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine \"transactionData\" dataset (preview of first few rows)\nhead(transactionData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#FFCCCB; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #EE4B2B; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🚩 Data Racoon *finds* Dirty Data! 🚩</b><br>\n  🦝: The \"DATE\" column is in an integer format (e.g. 43390) and needs to be converted to a proper date format. Let's clean it up!\n</div>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Note: DATE column uses Excel-style dates (43390, 43599, etc.) = days since 1899-12-30\n# Convert DATE to date format using \"as.Date()\" function\ntransactionData$DATE <- as.Date(transactionData$DATE, origin = \"1899-12-30\") \n\n#Now DATE column should be converted to its proper date format, let's take a look\nhead((transactionData),3)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Now I'll examine \"PROD_NAME\" column to check if all products are chips\nunique(transactionData$PROD_NAME) ","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#FFCCCB; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #EE4B2B; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🚩 Data Racoon *finds* More Dirty Data! 🚩</b><br>\n  🦝: \"PROD_NAME\" column contains some products that are not chips. This goes against our business objective! Let's fix it.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# First I'll summarize individual words in the PROD_NAME column to see if there are any products that are not chips\ncat(\"\\nIndividual Word Count in PROD_NAME Column\\n\\n\")\nproductWords <- transactionData %>%                                        \n  distinct(PROD_NAME) %>%   # keeps only unique product names\n  mutate(words = str_split(PROD_NAME, \" \")) %>%   # split product names into word lists\n  unnest(words) %>%   # flatten the word lists into individual rows\n  filter(!grepl(\"[0-9&]\", words), words != \"\") %>%   # remove blanks, special characters, digits                                                                         \n  count(words, sort = TRUE, name = \"count\") %>%   # count word frequencies and sort by count\n  slice_head(n = 20)                                                           \nprint(productWords)                                                        ","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# There are indeed non-chip products like salsa, but we're only interested in chips, so let's remove all salsa products\ntransactionData <- transactionData %>%\n  filter(!str_detect(tolower(PROD_NAME), \"salsa\"))\n\n# Check if key words like \"salsa\" appears\nsalsaWords <- productWords %>%\n  filter(str_detect(words, regex(\"salsa\", ignore_case = TRUE)))\nprint(salsaWords)\nprint(\"As shown by the result, all salsa products have been removed\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine summary statistics to search for any outliers and nulls\nsummary(transactionData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#FFCCCB; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #EE4B2B; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🚩 Data Racoon *finds* More Dirty Data! 🚩</b><br>\n  🦝: There are no nulls, but \"PROD_QTY\" column seems to have an outlier, where it correlates to the outlier in \"TOT_SALE\" column! Let's investigate.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filter to find the outlier \ntransactionData %>% \n    filter(PROD_QTY >= 6)\nprint(\"It looks like the same customer bought two transactions of 200 packets of chips. Let's see if this customer had other transactions\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Checking all transactions made by this one particular customer\ntransactionData %>%\n    filter(LYLTY_CARD_NBR == 226000)\nprint(\"We can confirm that this customer only made those two transactions over the year and is safe to assume that they are not an ordinary shopper but rather they're shopping for commerical purposes\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Let's remove this customer (loyalty card number) from further analysis\ntransactionData <- transactionData %>%\n    filter(LYLTY_CARD_NBR != 226000)\nsummary(transactionData)\nprint(\"The commerical customer who represented an outlier has been removed\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Now, let's look at the number of transaction lines over time to check for any data issues (e.g. missing data)\ntransactionSummary <- transactionData %>%\n    group_by(DATE) %>%    \n    summarise(transaction_count = n()) %>%   # new transaction_count col that counts num of rows in each date group\n    arrange(DATE)   # sort date by ASC order\nprint(transactionSummary)\nprint(\"There's only 364 rows = dates, meaning one date is missing\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Create a list of all dates from July 1, 2018 to June 30, 2019\ndate_sequence <- tibble(DATE = seq(as.Date(\"2018-07-01\"), as.Date(\"2019-06-30\"), by = \"day\"))\n\n# Join this list with the original transaction summary data\ntransactionsummaryFull <- date_sequence %>%\n  left_join(transactionSummary, by = \"DATE\")   # left join keeps all dates, even if there were no transactions during that missing date\nprint(transactionsummaryFull)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Format graphs first\ntheme_set(theme_bw())\ntheme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))\n\n# Plot transactions over time\nggplot(transactionsummaryFull, aes(x = DATE, y = transaction_count)) +\ngeom_line() +\nlabs(x = \"Day\", y = \"Number of transactions\", title = \"Transactions over time\") +\nscale_x_date(breaks = \"1 month\") +\ntheme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))\n\nprint(\"There is an increase in purchase in December and a small break in late December\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filter data to only show December, 2018\ndecemberData <- transactionsummaryFull %>%\n  filter(DATE >= as.Date(\"2018-12-01\") & DATE <= as.Date(\"2018-12-31\"))\n\n# Plot transactions in December\nggplot(decemberData, aes(x = DATE, y = transaction_count)) +   \n  geom_line() +\n  labs(x = \"Day\", y = \"Number of transactions\", title = \"Transactions in December 2018\") +\n  scale_x_date(breaks = \"1 day\", date_labels = \"%d-%b\") +\n  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))\n\nprint(\"There were an increase in sales during the lead up to Christmasand zero sales on Christmas Day as shops are closed\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Extract pack size by parsing numbers from PROD_NAME\ntransactionData <- transactionData %>%\n  mutate(PACK_SIZE = readr::parse_number(PROD_NAME))   # adds a new column \"packSize\" that extracts product size  from PROD_NAME\n\n# Count number of rows per PACK_SIZE and sort by PACK_SIZE\ntransactionData %>%\n  count(PACK_SIZE) %>%\n  arrange(PACK_SIZE)\n\nprint(\"Smallest size: 70g | Largest size: 380g | There seems to be no outlier/error\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Plot histogram for categorical variable)\nggplot(transactionData, aes(x = factor(PACK_SIZE))) +\n  geom_bar() +\n  labs(x = \"Pack Size (g)\", y = \"Number of Transactions\", title = \"Transactions by Pack Size\") ","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Create a new BRAND column by extracting the first word from PROD_NAME\ntransactionData <- transactionData %>%\n  mutate(BRAND = word(PROD_NAME, 1))\n\n# Check the result by counting each brand\ntransactionData %>%\n  count(BRAND) %>%\n  arrange(BRAND)   #sorting from A to Z to make it easier to catch different brand names that are the same brand","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#FFCCCB; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #EE4B2B; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🚩 Data Racoon *finds* More Dirty Data! 🚩</b><br>\n  🦝: Some different brand names like \"RED\" and \"RRD\" are actually from the same brand \"Red Rock Deli\". Let's combine them together!\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Replace brand names to reflect the same brand \ntransactionData <- transactionData %>%          \n  mutate(BRAND = case_when(                       # updates the BRAND column based on conditions\n    BRAND %in% c(\"Red\", \"RRD\") ~ \"RRD\",           # if BRAND is \"RED\" or \"RRD\", change it to \"RRD\"\n    BRAND %in% c(\"Doritos\", \"Dorito\") ~ \"Doritos\", # if BRAND is \"Doritos\" or \"Dorito\", change to \"Doritos\"\n    BRAND %in% c(\"Smiths\", \"Smith\") ~ \"Smiths\",   # if BRAND is \"Smiths\" or \"Smith\", change to \"Smiths\"\n    BRAND %in% c(\"Infuzions\", \"Infzns\") ~ \"Infuzions\", # if BRAND is \"Infuzions\" or \"Infzns\", change to \"Infuzions\"\n    BRAND %in% c(\"Sunbites\", \"Snbts\") ~ \"Sunbites\",   # if BRAND is \"Sunbites\" or \"Snbts\", change to \"Sunbites\"\n    TRUE ~ BRAND                                   # otherwise, keep the existing BRAND value\n  ))\n\n# Check brand names again\ntransactionData %>%\n  count(BRAND) %>%\n  arrange(BRAND)\nprint(\"Identical brands with different spelling of name have all been combined into one name\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>✅ Data Racoon *cleaned* All Dirty Data! ✅</b><br>\n  🦝: The \"transactionData\" dataset is now clean and tidy! Onto the next dataset.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🦝 Data Raccoon 🦝</b><br>\n  *digging* into customerData to uncover dirty data and patterns...\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine \"customerData\" dataset (internal structure)\nstr(customerData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine \"customerData\" dataset (preview of first few rows)\nhead(customerData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Examine summary statistics\nsummary(customerData)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Distribution of \"LIFESTAGE\" column\ncustomerData %>% \n  count(LIFESTAGE, sort = TRUE)\n\n# Visualization\ncustomerData %>%\n  ggplot(aes(x = LIFESTAGE)) +\n  geom_bar(fill = \"skyblue\") +\n  theme_minimal() +\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of Customer Life Stages\", x = \"Life Stage\", y = \"Count\") +\n  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Distribution of \"PREMIUM_CUSTOMER\" column\ncustomerData %>% \n  count(PREMIUM_CUSTOMER, sort = TRUE)\n\n# Visualize premium customer segment\ncustomerData %>%\n  ggplot(aes(x = PREMIUM_CUSTOMER)) +\n  geom_bar(fill = \"lightgreen\") +\n  theme_minimal() +\n  labs(title = \"Distribution of Premium Segments\", x = \"Segment\", y = \"Count\") ","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Merge transactionData to customerData\ndata <- left_join(transactionData, customerData, by = \"LYLTY_CARD_NBR\")   \n\n#keeps all rows from \"transactionData\", matches rows from customerData with matching values, else, fills in with NA","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Count any transactions that did not have a matched customer\nunmatched_n <- data %>%\n  filter(is.na(LIFESTAGE)) %>%   \n  nrow()\n\nprint(unmatched_n)        # shows the number of transactions with no customer match\nprint(\"Awesome, there are no nulls, which means all customers in the transactionData has been accounted for in the customerData\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Save this new cleaned dataset for Task 2\nwrite_csv(data, \"QVI_data.csv\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"height:5px; background-color:#0096FF;\"></div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h2 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight: bold;\"\"> 4. Data Analysis on Customer Segments  </h2>\n\n<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>📈 Data Analysis:</b><br>\n  In this stage, the two datasets (transactionData & customerData) have been cleaned and is ready for analysis. I'll be defining some metrics of interest throughout the analysis.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Load new merged dataset (transactionData + customerData)\nmergedData <- read_csv(\"/kaggle/working//QVI_data.csv\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 1st Metric of Interest: Total Sales Contributors 🔍 </b><br>\n  Who spends the most on chips? Describing customers by lifestage and how premium their general purchasing behavior is\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculate total sales by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM_CUSTOMER\nsalesbySegment <- mergedData %>%\n    group_by(LIFESTAGE, PREMIUM_CUSTOMER) %>%\n    summarize(TOT_SALES = sum(TOT_SALES, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   # calculate total sales per group, ignores missing values\n    arrange(desc(TOT_SALES)) %>%\n    ungroup()   # removes grouping for other further operations\n\nsalesbySegment","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Plot total sales by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM_CUSTOMER\nggplot(salesbySegment, aes(x = LIFESTAGE, y = TOT_SALES, fill = PREMIUM_CUSTOMER)) +\n    geom_col(position = 'dodge') +   # bar chart where 'dodge' ensures bars for each group appears next to each other for comparison rather than stacked\n    labs(title = \"Total Sales by Lifestage and Premium Segment\", x = \"Lifestage\", y = \"Total Sales\") +\n    theme_minimal() +\n    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 8))\n\nprint(\"We can see that the top 3 sales are coming from 1. 'Budget/OlderFamilies', 2. 'Mainstream/YoungSinglesCouples', 3. 'Mainstream/Retirees'\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 2nd Metric of Interest: Segment with Highest Population 🔍 </b><br>\n  How many customers are in each segment?\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Summarize number of customers by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM_CUSTOMER (to see if higher sales are due to there being more customers who buy chips)\n\ncustomerCount <- mergedData %>%\n    group_by(LIFESTAGE, PREMIUM_CUSTOMER) %>%\n    summarize(CUSTOMER_COUNT = n_distinct(LYLTY_CARD_NBR)) %>%   # counts unique customers\n    arrange(desc(CUSTOMER_COUNT)) %>%\n    ungroup()   # removes grouping for other further operations\n\ncustomerCount","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Plot number of customers by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM_CUSTOMER\n\nggplot(customerCount, aes(x = LIFESTAGE, y = CUSTOMER_COUNT, fill = PREMIUM_CUSTOMER)) +\n       geom_col(position = 'dodge') +\n       labs(title = \"Number of Customers by Lifestage and Premium Segment\", x = \"Lifestage\", y = \"Customer Count\") +\n       theme_minimal() +\n       theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))\n\nprint(\"A high customer count in 'Mainstream/YoungSinglesCouple' and 'Mainstream/Retirees' does indeed contribute to higher sales, but not as significant for 'Budget/OlderFamilies'\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 3rd Metric of Interest: Highest Average Units per Transaction 🔍 </b><br>\n  How many chips are bought per customer by segment?\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculate average units per customer \navgUnits <- mergedData %>%\n    group_by(LIFESTAGE, PREMIUM_CUSTOMER) %>%\n    summarize(AVG_UNITS = mean(PROD_QTY, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   # calculates average units per customer grouped by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM_CUSTOMER\n    arrange(desc(AVG_UNITS)) %>%\n    ungroup()   # removes grouping for other further operations\n\navgUnits","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Plot average units per customer\nggplot(avgUnits, aes(x = LIFESTAGE, y = AVG_UNITS, fill = PREMIUM_CUSTOMER)) +\n    geom_col (position = 'dodge') + \n    labs(title = \"Average Units Per Customer By Lifestage and Premium Segment\", x = \"Lifestage\", y = \"Average Units\") +\n    theme_minimal() +\n    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))\n\nprint(\"Young and older families purchase more chips per customer\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 4th Metric of Interest: Highest Avgerage Unit Price  🔍 </b><br>\n  What's the average chip price by customer segment\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Calculate average price per units\navgchipPrice <- mergedData %>%\n    group_by(LIFESTAGE, PREMIUM_CUSTOMER) %>%\n    summarize(AVG_UNIT_PRICE = sum(TOT_SALES, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(PROD_QTY, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   # to find price, divide sales by quantity \n    arrange(desc(AVG_UNIT_PRICE)) %>%\n    ungroup()   # removes grouping for other further operations\n\navgchipPrice","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Plot average price per units\nggplot(avgchipPrice, aes(x = LIFESTAGE, y = AVG_UNIT_PRICE, fill = PREMIUM_CUSTOMER)) +\n    geom_col(position = 'dodge') +\n    labs(title = \"Average Price Per Unit\", x = \"Lifestage\", y = \"Average Price\") +\n    theme_minimal() +\n    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))\n\nprint(\"Mainstream midage and young singles/couples are more willing to pay more per packet of chips compared to their budget and premium counterparts. Premium customers most likely prefer healthier snacks and would buy chips for entertainment as seen by fewer premium young and midage singles/couples. The difference across average price per unit is marginal nonetheless, so let's check if they're statistically different.\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Filter the data\nfilteredData <- mergedData %>%\n    filter(LIFESTAGE %in% c(\"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES\", \"MIDAGE SINGLES/COUPLES\")) %>%   # keeps only young or midage singles/couples\n    mutate(SEGMENT_GROUP = ifelse(PREMIUM_CUSTOMER == \"Mainstream\", \"Mainstream\", \"Other\"))   # creates a new column to label \"Mainstream\" vs others\n\n# Add a UNIT_PRICE column for t-test\nfilteredData <- filteredData %>%\n    mutate(UNIT_PRICE = TOT_SALES / PROD_QTY)\n\n# Perform the T-test\nt.test(UNIT_PRICE ~ SEGMENT_GROUP, data = filteredData)\n\nprint(\"p-value is extremely small (close to zero), meaning difference in means is highly statistically significant, very unlikely due to chance. 95% confidence interval from 0.316 to 0.531 means the difference in unit price between the groups is estimated to be between 31.6 cents and 35.1 cents. Test confirms that Mainstream midage and young singles/couples do pay significantly more per packet of chips compared to budget and premium groups.\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 Deep Dive into \"Mainstream, young singles/couples\"  🔍 </b><br>\n  Based on all metrics so far, our target segment (mainstream, young singles/couples) pays more per packet of chips than their budget and premium counterparts. Additionally, our target segment is top 3 in total sales and is the most populated segment. We'll certainly want to retain them. Let's uncover a few more insights about our new target segment.\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 4th Metric of Interest: Top Brand Preferences of Target Segment 🔍 </b><br>\n  What's the average chip price by customer segment\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Method | Descriptive Analysis | To find brand preference\n\n# Filter for mainstream, young singles/couples\ntargetSegment <- mergedData %>%\n    filter(LIFESTAGE == \"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES\", PREMIUM_CUSTOMER == \"Mainstream\")\n\n# Count total quantity purchased per brand by our target segment\nbrandPreference <- targetSegment %>%\n    group_by(BRAND) %>%\n    summarize(TOT_QTY = sum(PROD_QTY, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   # creates a total quantity column that sums quantity per brand\n    arrange(desc(TOT_QTY))   # sorts from most bought to least\nhead(brandPreference, 10)\n\nprint(\"It seems our target segment (mainstream, young singles/couple) prefers the Kettle brand the most. Now, what about packet size?\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px; text-align:center;\">\n  <b>🔎 4th Metric of Interest: Most Preferred Pack Sizes of Target Segment 🔍 </b><br>\n  What's the average chip price by customer segment\n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Method 1 | Descriptive Analysis | To find size preference\n\n# Filter for mainstream, young singles/couples\ntargetSegment <- mergedData %>%\n    filter(LIFESTAGE == \"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES\", PREMIUM_CUSTOMER == \"Mainstream\")\n\n# Count total quantity purchased per brand by our target segment\nbrandPreference <- targetSegment %>%\n    group_by(PACK_SIZE) %>%\n    summarize(TOT_QTY = sum(PROD_QTY, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   # creates a total quantity column that sums quantity per brand\n    arrange(desc(TOT_QTY))   # sorts from most bought to least\nhead(brandPreference, 10)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Method 2 | Affinity Analysis | To find size preference\n\n# Create a new column for group labels\nmergedData <- mergedData %>%\n  mutate(TARGET_GROUP = ifelse(LIFESTAGE == \"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES\" & PREMIUM_CUSTOMER == \"Mainstream\", \"Target\", \"Other\"))\n\n# Run t-test on PACK_SIZE\nttestResult <- t.test(PACK_SIZE ~ TARGET_GROUP, data = mergedData)   # compares pack sizes between target group and other groups\n\nttestResult\n\nprint(\"Based on methods 1 and 2, our target segment (mainstream, singles/couples) prefers the pack size of 175 grams. The affinity analysis here concludes that its apriori algorithm resulted in a rule that, 'since our target segment (mainstream, singles/couples) buys the Kettle brand, they also buy a pack size of 170g.' \")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<div style=\"height:5px; background-color:#0096FF;\"></div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h2 style=\"font-family:verdana; font-weight: bold;\"\"> 5. Insights and Recommendation  </h2>\n\n<div style=\"background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-left:5px solid #0096FF; font-family:Verdana; font-size:14px;\">\n  <b>💭 Data Share:</b><br>\n  Throughout task one, the datasets given by our client has been cleaned, explored, visualized, and analyzed. All insights and recommendations will be provided in this section. \n</div>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**INSIGHTS**\n\n**Top 3 Total Sales Contributors:**\n1.  *Older Families* (Budget): $156,864\n   \n3.  *Young Singles/Couples* (Mainstream): $147,582\n\n5.  *Retirees* (Mainstream): $145,169\n\n**Top 3 Most Populated Segment:**\n1. *Young Singles/Couples* (Mainstream): 7,917 \n   \n3. *Retirees* (Mainstream): 6,358 \n\n4. *Older Singles/Couples* (Mainstream): 4,858 \n\n\n**Segments with Highest Average Units per Transaction:**\n1. *Older Families* (Mainstream): 1.9488 \n   \n3. *Older Families* (Premium): 1.9455 \n\n4. *Older Families* (Budget): 1.9454\n\n\n**Segments with Highest Average Unit Price:**\n1. *Young Singles/Couples* (Mainstream): $4.07 \n   \n3. *Midage Singles/Couples* (Mainstream): $3.99\n\n4. *New Families* (Mainstream): $3.94\n\n\n**Top Brand Preferences of Target Segment:**\n1. *Kettle*\n   \n3. *Doritos*\n\n4. *Pringles*\n\n\n**Preferred Pack Sizes of Target Segment:**\n1. *175g*\n   \n3. *150g*\n\n4. *134g*\n\n**RECOMMENDATION:**\n\nBased on the analysis, I recommend to focus marketing efforts on ***Young Singles/Couples (Mainstream)*** as they stand out as the strongest ***segment to target*** for future product promotion and targeted marketing. They are among the ***top contributors to total sales*** at $147,582, and represent the ***largest customer base*** with 7,917 customers. Despite not leading in average units per transaction, they are the ***most willing to pay more*** per packet of chips compared to their budget and premium counterparts, suggesting they purchase higher priced products. \n\nAdditionally, the top brand preference is ***Kettle*** and the most preferred pack size is ***175g***.","metadata":{}}]}